cs.CR, cs.LO, cs.IT, cs.CY, cs.DS 

This paper deals with the security requirement of electronic voting protocols, specifically coercion resistance. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The paper also proposes a new definition of coercion resistance based on an epistemic approach, which involves knowledge and belief. This could potentially fall under cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) or cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also involves the analysis of voting protocols, which could fall under cs.CY (Computers and Society) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
